<title>UK: UK tv advertising expenditure rose 4.1 pct in 1996.</title>
<headline>UK tv advertising expenditure rose 4.1 pct in 1996.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-07-16</dateline>
<text>
<p>Advertising expenditure in Britain rose across all media in 1996, including a 4.1-percent rise in television to 2.75 billion pounds ($4.6 billion) on an inflation-adjusted basis, a UK trade group said on Wednesday.</p>
<p>The Advertising Association, in its 1997 Media Pocket Book, said advertising expenditure for all press rose 4.4 percent in real terms to 5.28 billion pounds in 1996. National newspapers rose 2.8 percent, regional newspapers gained 2.5 percent, consumer magazines rose 6.7 percent, business and professional publications jumped 8.6 percent and directories increased 5.7 percent.</p>
<p>Radio spending has risen 13.4 percent to 284 million pounds since 1996, outdoor and transport gained 10.0 percent to 352 million pounds, direct mail gained 20.8 percent to 1.16 billion pounds and cinema rose 3.3 percent to 60 million pounds.</p>
